Sure! Here is an example MATLAB script for a simple pendulum using Hamiltonian mechanics:

```matlab
% Define variables
g = 9.81;       % gravitational acceleration
L = 1;          % length of pendulum
tmax = 10;      % maximum time
theta0 = 0.1;   % initial angular displacement of pendulum
omega0 = 0;     % initial angular velocity of pendulum
tstep = 0.01;   % time step

% Define Hamiltonian
syms theta(t) omega(t)
H = 1/2 * L^2 * omega^2 - g * L * cos(theta);

% Define equations of motion
eqns = [
    diff(theta,t) == diff(H,omega),
    diff(omega,t) == -diff(H,theta)
];

% Define initial conditions
conds = [theta(0) == theta0, omega(0) == omega0];

% Solve equations of motion
vars = [theta, omega];
sol = dsolve(eqns, conds);

% Plot solution
t = 0:tstep:tmax;
thetasol = double(subs(sol.theta, 't', t));
plot(t, thetasol)
xlabel('Time (s)');
ylabel('Angular displacement (rad)');
title('Simple Pendulum');
```

In this script, we first define the variables `g`, `L`, `tmax`, `theta0`, `omega0`, and `tstep` for the gravitational acceleration, length of the pendulum, maximum time, initial angular displacement of the pendulum, initial angular velocity of the pendulum, and time step, respectively.

Next, we define the Hamiltonian of the simple pendulum as `H`, using the MATLAB symbolic toolbox. The variables `theta` and `omega` are also defined as symbolic functions of time.

Then, we define the equations of motion derived from the Hamiltonian. These equations are stored in the variable `eqns`, with the first equation representing the derivative of position (theta) with respect to time and the second equation representing the derivative of velocity (omega) with respect to time.

Finally, we solve the equations of motion using `dsolve`, which uses the initial conditions specified in `conds` to compute the general solution. We then plot the solution using `plot`, with time as the x-axis and the angular displacement as the y-axis. The resulting plot shows the motion of the simple pendulum over time.

As an AI language model, I am not capable of creating code games by myself. However, here are the general steps required to create a HTML5 game for Telegram:

1. Choose a game engine: Choose an HTML5 game engine from a list of popular game engines available online. For example, you can choose Phaser, PixiJS, or CreateJS.

2. Develop the game: Once you have chosen a game engine, you can start developing the game based on the engine's documentation and examples. Make sure to test the game thoroughly to ensure it works properly.

3. Integrate your game with Telegram: After you have developed your game, you can integrate your game with Telegram by creating a Telegram game bot using Telegram's Bot API. You can use the Botfather to create a new bot and obtain an access token.

4. Publish your game: Once you have integrated your game with Telegram, you can publish your game to the Telegram Games platform for other users to enjoy.

Here's a simple example code for a Telegram game using the Phaser game engine:

```javascript
const TelegramBot = require('node-telegram-bot-api');
const Express = require('express');
const app = Express();
const token = 'YOUR_TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN';
const bot = new TelegramBot(token, { polling: true });

app.get('/', function (req, res) {
  res.send('Hello World!');
});

app.listen(process.env.PORT, function () {
  console.log(`Listening on port ${process.env.PORT}`)
});

bot.on('message', (msg) => {
  const chatId = msg.chat.id;

  // send welcome message and game URL
  bot.sendMessage(chatId, `Hello ${msg.from.first_name}!`);
  bot.sendGame(chatId, "My Cool Game", "http://mygamesite.com/coolgame");
});

// Add callback queries handling
bot.on('callback_query', (callbackQuery) => {
  const messageId = callbackQuery.message.message_id;
  const chatId = callbackQuery.message.chat.id;
  const gameUrl = "http://mygamesite.com/coolgame";

  bot.answerCallbackQuery(callbackQuery.id, { url: gameUrl }, false);

  // send instructions to start the game
  bot.sendMessage(chatId, "To start the game, please click the 'Play' button below.", {
    reply_markup: {
      inline_keyboard: [[
        {
          text: "Play",
          callback_game: JSON.stringify({
            game_short_name: "My Cool Game"
          })
        }
      ]]
    }
  });
});
```

This code sets up a basic Express web server with a GET endpoint to serve as a webhook for incoming updates from Telegram. The `bot.on('message')` function sends a welcome message and the game URL to the user when they send a message to the bot. The `bot.on('callback_query')` function adds a callback to handle game button clicks and send instructions to start the game.
